  "prompt": "What is the difference between shear stress and shear strain?",
  "response": "Let me explain the key differences between shear stress and shear strain:\n\nShear Stress:\n1. Definition: Force per unit area applied parallel to a surface\n2. Measures the internal force causing deformation\n3. Units: Pascals (Pa) or N/m\u00b2\n4. Represented by \u03c4 (tau)\n5. Indicates the intensity of the applied force\n6. Relates to the material's resistance to sliding\n\nShear Strain:\n1. Definition: Measure of deformation caused by shear stress\n2. Represents the angular displacement between parallel planes\n3. Dimensionless (no units)\n4. Represented by \u03b3 (gamma)\n5. Shows how much a material has been distorted\n6. Calculated as the tangent of the angle of deformation\n\nKey Differences:\n- Stress is a force-related property\n- Strain is a displacement-related property\n- Stress causes strain\n- Stress is measured in force per unit area\n- Strain is a measure of deformation\n- Relationship between them depends on material properties (shear modulus)\n\nIn summary, shear stress is the applied force, while shear strain is the resulting deformation.",
